@node Indent "Indent.ced"
@prev Indent

@{fg highlight}NAME@{fg text}
      @{b}Indent.ced@{ub} - indent line/block.

@{fg highlight}SYNOPSIS@{fg text}
      @{b}Indent.ced@{ub}

@{fg highlight}DESCRIPTION@{fg text}
      @{b}Indent.ced@{ub} can operate on a line or block. If a block is marked, then
  it will work on this block otherwise it will affect current line. This
  script inserts one tabulation char at the beginning of current line/each
  line in block and then restores cursor's position.

@{fg highlight}BUGS@{fg text}
      @{b}Indent.ced@{ub} doesn't work well with large blocks (>64KB). Also, for
  large blocks it may take some time to indent them. Cursor positioning
  after indenting is not always perfect for blocks.
@endnode

@node MakeComment "MakeComment.ced"

@{fg highlight}NAME@{fg text}
      @{b}MakeComment.ced@{ub} - make boxed comment in current file.

@{fg highlight}SYNOPSIS@{fg text}
      @{b}MakeComment.ced@{ub} [@{b}SHORT@{ub}|@{b}LONG@{ub}] [@{b}PAS@{ub}|@{b}P@{ub}|@{b}CPP@{ub}|@{b}HPP@{ub}|@{b}ADA@{ub}|@{b}BAS@{ub}|@{b}ASM@{ub}|@{b}S@{ub}|@{b}MAK@{ub}]

@{fg highlight}DESCRIPTION@{fg text}
      @{b}MakeComment.ced@{ub} makes boxed comment in current file. If a block is
  highlighted, then this block will be commented. If no block is marked, then
  current line will be commented. There are three types of comments:

@{i}/*
**  @{b}Short comments@{ub} - string is not centered
*/@{ui},

@{i}/* @{b}Line comments@{ub} - line is taken into comments */@{ui} and

@{i}/***************************************************************************/
/*                   @{b}Long comments@{ub} - string is centered                    */
/***************************************************************************/@{ui}

      You can choose the chars that form a comment by giving a second
  parameter. If you don't, then the decision will be taken upon file's
  extension. If you specify a language not known to @{b}MakeComment@{ub} then
  default (C-style) chars will be used.

@{fg highlight}PARAMETERS@{fg text}
      @{b}SHORT@{ub} - use short form (default);
      @{b}LINE@{ub} - use line form;
      @{b}LONG@{ub} - use long form;
      @{b}PAS@{ub} - use Pascal style (@{b}(*@{ub} and @{b}*)@{ub});
      @{b}P@{ub}   - use old Pascal style (@{b}{*@{ub} and @{b}*}@{ub});
      @{b}CPP@{ub} - use C++ style (@{b}//@{ub});
      @{b}HPP@{ub} - use C++ style (@{b}//@{ub});
      @{b}ADA@{ub} - use Ada style (@{b}--@{ub});
      @{b}BAS@{ub} - use BASIC style (@{b}'@{ub});
      @{b}ASM@{ub} - use Assembler style (@{b}*@{ub});
      @{b}S@{ub}   - use Assembler style (@{b};@{ub});
      @{b}MAK@{ub} - use Make style (@{b}#@{ub});

@{fg highlight}BUGS@{fg text}
      @{b}MakeComment.ced@{ub} doesn't work well with large blocks (>64KB). Also,
  for large blocks it may take some time to make a comment.

@{fg highlight}NOTES@{fg text}
      You can add your own styles by editing lines 29-37 of script (line 28
  holds default style). @{b}Len.@{ub} is a number of chars that form a comment, @{b}Beg.@{ub}
  holds @{b}Len.@{ub} chars that begin a comment, @{b}End.@{ub} holds @{b}Len.@{ub} chars that end a
  comment and @{b}Fill.@{ub} is a char to be used as a fill.
      For example, to quote a block (as in a mail program) you could add the
  following style:
  @{i}@{b}Len.@{ub}=1;	@{b}Beg.@{ub}=">";	@{b}End.@{ub}="<";	@{b}Fill.@{ub}=" ";@{ui}
  and use @{b}SHORT@{ub} parameter.
@endnode

@node MultiView "MultiView.ced"

@{fg highlight}NAME@{fg text}
      @{b}MultiView.ced@{ub} - show current file

@{fg highlight}SYNOPSIS@{fg text}
      @{b}MultiView.ced@{ub} [@{b}BACKDROP@{ub}]

@{fg highlight}DESCRIPTION@{fg text}
      This script will first save current file (if any changes have been
  made to it) and then show it. The method of showing the file will be
  chosen according to it's type. E.g., if it is AmigaGuide® file, it will
  be shown as a guide, if it is a picture, it will be shown as a picture,
  etc.

@{fg highlight}PARAMETERS@{fg text}
      @{b}BACKDROP@{ub} - use a backdrop window (only if @{i}CEd@{ui} is on its own screen).

@{fg highlight}NOTES@{fg text}
      A file is being shown with @{i}MultiView@{ui}. Files will be shown on @{i}CEd@{ui}'s
  screen (if public) or on Workbench, using @{i}CEd@{i}'s font.
@endnode

@node Outdent "Outdent.ced"

@{fg highlight}NAME@{fg text}
      @{b}Outdent.ced@{ub} - Outdent line/block.

@{fg highlight}SYNOPSIS@{fg text}
      @{b}Outdent.ced@{ub}

@{fg highlight}DESCRIPTION@{fg text}
      @{b}Outdent.ced@{ub} can operate on a line or block. If a block is marked,
  then it will work on this block otherwise it will affect current line.
  This scripts removes first white character (tabulation or space) from the
  beginning of current line/each line in block reversing effect of
  @{"Indent.ced" link Indent}. Lines not beginning with a white char are not affected.

@{fg highlight}BUGS@{fg text}
      @{b}Outdent.ced@{ub} doesn't work well with large blocks (>64KB). Also, for
  large blocks it may take some time to outdent them. Cursor positioning
  after outdenting is not always perfect for blocks.
@endnode

@node Paginate "Paginate.ced"

@{fg highlight}NAME@{fg text}
      @{b}Paginate.ced@{ub} - add page numbers and page breaks

@{fg highlight}SYNOPSIS@{fg text}
      @{b}Paginate.ced@{ub} @{i}LinesPerPage@{ui} [@{b}FF@{ub}]

@{fg highlight}DESCRIPTION@{fg text}
      @{b}Paginate.ced@{ub} inserts page numbers into current file. Numbers are
  centered and enclosed between '-' chars. Example:
                                    @{i}- 1 -@{ui}
      Numbers are added at the end of each page. Optionally, page breaks
  may be inserted after page numbers.

@{fg highlight}PARAMETERS@{fg text}
      @{i}LinesPerPage@{ui} - number of lines per page;
      @{b}FF@{ub} - add page break after each page number.

@{fg highlight}BUGS@{fg text}
      A file being paginated may not contain page breaks.

@{fg highlight}NOTES@{fg text}
      Number of lines per page can not be obtained from @{i}CygnusEd@{ui} - you must
  provide it yourself. Read it from your printer preferences and give as a
  parameter.
@endnode

@node Preview "Preview.ced"

@{fg highlight}NAME@{fg text}
      @{b}Preview.ced@{ub} - show file with formatting

@{fg highlight}SYNOPSIS@{fg text}
      @{b}Preview.ced@{ub} [@{b}BACKDROP@{ub}]

@{fg highlight}DESCRIPTION@{fg text}
      A big disadvantage of @{i}CygnusEd@{ui} is its inability to show formatting
  (italics, bold, colors). This script will show current file with ANSI
  formatting.

@{fg highlight}PARAMETERS@{fg text}
      @{b}BACKDROP@{ub} - opens @{i}MultiView@{ui} as a backdrop (only if @{i}CEd@{ui} is on its own
  screen).

@{fg highlight}NOTES@{fg text}
      A file is being shown with @{i}MultiView@{ui}, as a clipboard. Files will
  be shown on @{i}CEd@{ui}'s screen (if public) or on Workbench, using @{i}CEd@{ui}'s font.
  This script can not properly show AmigaGuide® files, but since it passes
  data through clipboard, it may be more suitable for user without HD.
@endnode

@node Stats "Stats.ced"

@{fg highlight}NAME@{fg text}
      @{b}Stats.ced@{ub} - display file's statistics

@{fg highlight}SYNOPSIS@{fg text}
      @{b}Stats.ced@{ub}

@{fg highlight}DESCRIPTION@{fg text}
      This script gives basic statistics (size, number of lines, number of
  words, number of sentences) about current file. You can also get block's
  statistics (if a block is marked). This macro is much faster that @{i}ADPro@{ui}'s
  one, because it uses ARexx's internal functions to do calculations.

@{fg highlight}BUGS@{fg text}
      This script doesn't work well for files/blocks larger than 64KB. This
  is because ARexx's string are limited to that size. I'm not going to fix
  this bug since it is not my fault.
      Also, the words are counted as ARexx words (separated by spaces)
  rather than @{i}CEd@{ui}'s words (separated by non-alphanumeric chars).
@endnode

@node Undo "Undo.ced"
@next Undo

@{fg highlight}NAME@{fg text}
      @{b}Undo.ced@{ub} - undo multiple changes

@{fg highlight}SYNOPSIS@{fg text}
      @{b}Undo.ced@{ub}

@{fg highlight}DESCRIPTION@{fg text}
      This script undoes multiple changes made by one of other scripts from
  MCEd package. If no changes has been recorded, it will just undo last
  change. For example, one call to @{b}Undo.ced@{ub} will remove all changes made by
  @{"Paginate.ced" link Paginate}, @{"MakeComment.ced" link MakeComment}, @{"Indent.ced" link Indent} or @{"Outdent.ced" link Outdent}.

@{fg highlight}NOTES@{fg text}
      If you have written a script and want it to be compatible with
  @{b}Undo.ced@{ub} then do the following:
  · copy procedure @{i}UndoClipName@{ui} from this script (lines 41-43);
  · count number of changes your script makes;
  · @{i}CALL SetClip(UndoClipName(),G.Ops)@{ui}
      @{b}Undo.ced@{ub} maintains separate undo queue for each opened file.
@endnode

